# TypeScript Testing Standards

## Test stack

- **Runner:** Vitest (preferred) or Jest — match existing `package.json` in `services/dashboard/`.
- **Component tests:** React Testing Library (`@testing-library/react`).
- **API mocking:** MSW or typed mocks — never untyped `jest.fn()` returning `any`.

## No `any` in tests

```typescript
// WRONG
const mockFetch = jest.fn() as any;

// RIGHT
const mockListAgents = vi.fn<[], Promise<AgentRecord[]>>();
mockListAgents.mockResolvedValue([fixtureAgent()]);
```

## Test naming

- File: `ComponentName.test.tsx` or `feature-name.test.ts`
- Case: `describe("ComponentName", () => { it("shows error when API fails", ...) })`
- Prefer behaviour descriptions over implementation details.

## Component tests — user-centric queries

```typescript
// WRONG — tests implementation detail
expect(wrapper.find(".spinner")).toHaveLength(1);

// RIGHT — tests what the user sees
render(<AgentList />);
expect(screen.getByRole("status", { name: /loading/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
```

## Async patterns

```typescript
// WRONG — missing await, flaky
it("loads agents", () => {
    render(<AgentList />);
    expect(screen.getByText("Dev Agent")).toBeInTheDocument();
});

// RIGHT
it("loads agents", async () => {
    render(<AgentList />);
    expect(await screen.findByText("Dev Agent")).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

## Cross-tenant and auth UI

- Dashboard is org-scoped: tests must set org context in providers or route params.
- Never assert on raw tokens or API keys in DOM snapshots.

## Coverage expectations

- New components: render + primary interaction + error state.
- Hooks: success path, error path, and loading state.
- See `23-testing-strategy.mdc` for repo-wide coverage gates.
